{"/service/ndnp/mdu/batch_mdu_easton_ver02/data/sn89060127/00279521961/1924011901/0029.xml":{"full_text":"Saturday, January 19, 1924\nBUSINESS POINTERS.\nBuy your Hats at Callahan\u2019s.\nBuy our guaranteed Boots at Cal\nlahan\u2019s.\nPure Country Lard at Hillman\u2019s\nMarket.\nDress yourself from head to foot\nat Callahan\u2019s.\nWANTED Hogs at Hillman's\nMarket.\nIt is the style to give Photographs\nthis year. We have the best styles at\nHarris\u2019 Studio.\nHome made Sausage and Scrapple\nat HILLMAN\u2019S MARKET\nWANTED\u2014IOO men at the Baptist\nChurch every Sunday morning.\nH. B. PILCHARD.\nWill your cosy home be closed to\nyour family when you have gone?\nMetropolitan Life Insurance Co.\nYou will find Pure Mountain Buck\nwheat flour and home ground table\nhominy at EAGLE MILLS.\nFOR RENT\u2014Apartment of four\nrooms. Possession Feb. 1. Apply to\n612 Market St. 1-5-tf.\nFOR SALE\u2014AII wool bed blankets,\nsl2 per pair. Apply to\nFRANK E. HUDSON.\nWANTED \u2014Large young chickens.\nAlso eggs. B. F. Sturgis, comer of\nVine street and Clarke avenue. Tele\nphone 119.\nFOR RENT\u2014Three desirable of\nfices in the Woolworth Building. Im\nmediate possession.\nl-5-4t. M. L. VEASEY.\nBring your eggs to us. We pay the\nhighest market cash price.\nAMERICAN STORES CO.,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nSUPPOSE\u2014You buy your life in\nsurance with no uncertainty results.\nBuy it in\nMetropolitan Life Insurance Co.\nNOTICE\u2014I am prepared to make\n---all kinds of fancy pies, at reasonable\nprices\n1-19-tf. MRS. C. O. HUFFMAN.\nSTORE FOR RENT\u2014January Ist.\nNow occupied by American Store,\nFurther information at\nFISHER\u2019S BARGAIN STORE.\nFOR RENT\u2014Rear apartment over\nA. H. Stevens store on Market street.\nApply to\nJan. 12-tf. A. H. STEVENS.\nFOR RENT Desirable apart\nment. Apply to\nE. CARMEL WILSON,\n12-29-tf. 828 Second St.\nStart the New Year right. Learn\nbarber trade in few weeks. Write\nTri-City Barber School, 817 E. Balti\nmore St., Baltimore, Md. 12-29-4 t.\nEGGS WANTED whites and\nbrowns. Live poultry. Highest cash\nprices paid for .same.\nG. H. EVANS.\nNOTICE\u2014 Get your house -moved\nby the house mover, who has had 15\nyears experience in moving all size\nbuildings. G. T. Groton. Parlcsley, Va\nEggs and Poultry wanted. Don\u2019t\nhold broilers as Market is inclined\nlower. Comer Vine street and Clarke\nsve. Phone 119. B. F. STURGIS.\nFOR RENT\u2014Six room house, with\nconveniences. Possession February 1.\nApply to\nl-12-2t. BENJ. GIVARZ.\nFOR RENT\u2014Present location of\nCitizens Bank. Will be vacated Feb\nruary Ist. Apply to\nDec. 29. QUINCE ASHBURN.\nWANTED\u2014A middle-aged woman\nfor housekeeping. Experience neces\nsary. Apply to\nMRS. M. I. HEILIG,\n1-19-tf. Clarke Ave.\nFOR SALE CHEAP lOO Mule\nBridles, Riding Saddles, Back Bands,\nRain Coats, Arties and Boots.\nG. CLEVE TOWNSEND,\n1-6-tf. 406 Clarke Ave.\n\u201cBABY CHlX\u2019\u2019\u2014Place orders now\nfor Baby Chix as my hatching space\nis limited, and am booking orders\ndaily. Phone 119 ,comer Vine street\nand Clarke avenue.\nB. F. STURGIS.\nWANTED\u2014Young woman in coun\ntry home to assist light housekeep\ning, and care of invalid woman. Good\nhome and wages to proper party.\nMust give reference. Apply to Demo\ncrat office. Nov-24-tf.\nNOTICE\u2014 Custom hatching and\nday old chicks hatched from our vig\norous strain of S. C. White Leghorns.\nG. G. VON SICK,\nP. O. Westover, Md.\nJan 19, 3t. Costen, Md.\nFOR SALE Farm near Wel\nboume, containing about 100 acres\nwith 60 to 70 acres well set in pine\ntimber. Will sell as a whole or sepa\nrate. Possession at once. Farm sow\ned in rye.\nDec 29 E. J. REID.\nOyster roasts will continue during\nthe season. Those desiring service\nalong my line can communicate with\nme by phone at Thomas Wharton\u2019s\nstore. B. DISHAROON,\nSep-29-tf. Stockton,. Md.\nFOR RENT\u2014Ground floor apart\nment of dwelling on Willow street\nnow occupied as law offices of Ewell\nCh'ld. Possession January 1, 1924.\nApply to\nL. PAUL EWELL,\nAttomey-at-Law,\nPocomoke City, Md.\nWill take a limited number of voice\npupils at my home at King\u2019s Creek,\nor will teach a class of ten or more in\nchorus singring in Pocomoke City.\nItalian bel canto method used, which\nis perhaps the best for preserving and\ndeveloping the voice. Phone Princess\nAnne 46-F-3, or address R. F. D., No.\nH 2, Westover, Md.\n|-i9-4t. MRS. IDA CARTER.\nWhen you find ft man who speaks\nin unfavorable terms of insurance,\nyou may conclude that he is without\nits protections and that its benefits\nare unknown to him.\nMetropolitan Life Insurance Co.\ns Consult the Landscape Gardner a\nbout your garden problems, just as\nyou do a doctor or a lawyer. Avoid\nt mistakes and get results. Interviews\nupon request. Terms reasonable, ac\ncording to service rendered. Emily\nS. Kauffman, R. 1, Westover, Md.\nFOR SALE\u2014One hundred and thir\nty-two shares Standard Wholesale\nPhosphate and Acid Works, Inc.\nstock. This is Standard Fertilizer\ni Company\u2019s stock, and its par is S2O\nper share. If interested write\nH. A. NOCK,.\nt 1-19-tf. Onley, Va.\nBALTlMO\u00dfE\u2014Established Moving\nPicture and Vaudeville Theatre, busi\nness for sale, now in full operation.\n$350 weekly gross earnings. Owner\nretiring. Price $2,950. Will accept\ntwo-thirds cash; balance on good se\ncurity. If necessary will teach buyer\nbusiness. Triflers and curiosity seek\ners need not answer. Act quickly.\nAddress Manager, Room 237 Equit\nable Bldg., Baltimore, Md.\nSUPPOSE! \u2014If your children were\nwithout food to-day, what would you\nnot do to supply their need? If your\nlandlord were threatening to-day to\nevict your family, how strenuous\nwould be your efforts to prevent it?\nHave you seen to it that such disas\nters will not overtake them in the fu\nture, when you are no longer here to\nprotect them?\nMetropolitan Life Insurance Co.\nSTOCKTON NEWS\nMrs. Thomas Wharton, accompani\ned her mother to Baltimore this week.\nMrs. Purnell has gone for special\ntreatment of the eyes.\nMr. W. H. Marshall is confined to\nhis home on account of illness.\nMr. William Hudson\u2019s house on Pin\ney Island was burned last Monday\nmorning, caused by a defective chim\nney. Mr, Horace Trader and family\nwere occupying the house and lost\nquite a good bit of their furniture.\nMrs. Edwin Hancock is quite ill at\nher home near the Bay.\nMisses Mary Hyland and Mabel\n-Jones were week-end guests of Mrs.\nWilliam Nock at .her home near the\nBay.\nThe M. P. Church has had electrici- 1\nty installed and Sunday evening the 1\naudience enjoyed the electric lights\nfor the first time. Rev. J. P. George\nwho has been ill was able to fill the\npulpit Sunday evening.\n\nMr. W. Rowley is on the sick list\nthis week. Also little Misses Leah, 1\nIsabel and Barbara Zimmerman, and\nMrs. Warren Smith who has been\nquite ill is now improving.\nMrs. J. W. Tull has returned from\na visit to friends in New York.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Hickman, Mrs.\nW. H. Marshall and Mrs. Neal Hick\nman attended the funeral of Mrs.\nCarrie Townsend in Pocomoke City\nlast Sunday.\nMr. William Brattan, of Camden,\nwas a guest last Sunday, of his sister,\nMrs. John Peyton.\nMrs. Deborah Waterfield is the\nguest of her niece, Mrs. James B.\n'Hudson.\nMrs. John Sharpley spent part of\nthis week with his sister, Mrs. Bessie\nHouston.\nMiss Elizabeth Taylor wds home\nfrom Philadelphia for the week-end.\nMr. Asa Pollitt and sister, Mrs.\nMason, are in Wilmington where they\nwere called to the death bed of their\nj father last Friday night.\nCUSTOM HATCHING\u2014DAY OLD\nCHICKS.\nS. C. W. Leghorn chicks of high\nquality, the big husky kind all hatch-!\ned from old hen eggs. The hens from l\nwhich the eggs come are Hogan test-i\ned are in free range and are wonder- i\nful layers of large white eggs. I\n1 have 23 years experience which counts\nfor something, in the quality and\nnumber of chicks I can hatch for you.!\nI have patrons I have hatched for for\n10 and 12 years.\nI use, sell, and recommend the\nMagic Brooder, the best out. Send\nfor circular.\nCOMMUNITY HATCHERY\ns H. W. Taylor, Prop.\nBERLIN, MARYLAND,\nGIVARZ STORE NEWS\nAgency for American Lady Cor\nsets. There are no better.\nIf in need of a Coat, Sait or Dress,\nvisit our second floor department.\nThe only correct patterns are the\nz Butterick. We sell them.\nNone better than ready-to-wear in\nladies\u2019 goods than we carry,\ni New arrivals in Coats, Suits, and\nj Dresses. It is the biggest, and best;\ns and most reasonable priepd line wfe\nhave ever had. Give us a call.\nBENJAMIN GIVARZ.\nPocomoke City, Md.'\nWORCESTER DEMOCRAT, POCOMOKE CITY, MARYLAND\nLOCAL AND PERSONAL\nl Mrs. H. B. Pilchard is visiting her\nsister in Suffolk, Va.\nGodfrey Child, Esq., spent last\nweek-end in Baltimore.\nMr. Linwood T. Ellis spent last\nweek-end in Baltimore.\nMiss Mary Costen spent a part of\nthe week in Philadelphia.\nMiss Nellie Grice, of Cape Charles,\nVa., spent the week end with friends\nhere.\nMrs. Eugene S. Maddox spent the\nearly part of the week in Philadel\nphia.\nMiss Maude Berry, of Delmar, vis\nited Misses Anne and Evelyn White,\nthis week.\nMrs. William Benson and son have\nreturned home after a visit to friends\nin Parksley.\nMr. W. K. Funk and Mr. Brice\nBounds made a business trip to Salis\nbury on Sunday.\nMrs. Mattie Henderson left Tues\nday for Florida. She was accom\npanied by Mrs. Carie Henderson of\nBaltimore.\nMr. and Mrs. A. W. Price, of Salis\nbury, spent the week-end with -Mrs.\nPrice\u2019s mother, Mrs. John H. Blades\nof Walnut street.\nMr. Beverly Crowson left Sunday\nfor Fort Worth, Texas, where he will\ntake a two year\u2019s course at the South\nWestern Theological Seminary.\nMessrs. C. L. Vincent and A. C.\nHumphreys, of Snow Hill, and E. H.\nTaylor, of Stockton, were among the\ncallers at the Democrat office Tues\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Franklin West motor\ned to Wilmington, Del., and spent the\nearly part of the week with the lat\nter\u2019s parents, Mr. and Mrs. D. C.\nArmstrong.\nMr. Milton L. Veasey and Miss Isa\nbel Veasey were among the number of\nWestern Maryland Alumni that at\ntended a banquet given in Salisbury\nFriday night.\nMr. and Mrs. Milton L. Veasey\nspent the week in New York looking\nafter new spring and summer mer\nchandise for the Hargis Department\nstore of this city.\n__\nBAftGtS I\nj; DEPARTMENT STORE j;\nPOCOMOKE\ni| Two Important Sales\nREMNANT SALE I\nWEDNESDAY, JAN. 23\nBeginning promptly at 9 A. M.\nif THIS SALE WILL BE ONE OF THE LARGEST REMNANT\nO SALES WE HAVE EVER HELD. HUNDREDS OF YARDS OF o\nNEW, FRESH MATERIALS HAVE BEEN CUT IN DESIRABLE\nJ; LENGTHS AND WILL BE PUT ON SALE AT RIDICULOUSLY I!\n|o LOW PRICES. O\n\nij Twelve Large Merchandise Tables Will Be Used To ij\niij Display the Remnants and Reduced Goods ij\no\nO\no\n4\no\no n\no o\nIj Final Reduction in Ready-to-Wear Ij\nO 4\nAll Winter Apparel, Consisting of Coats,\nSuits, and Dresses Marked Down\nto Cost and Below\nn n\nn o\nJ Thee low prices go into effect immediately. Don\u2019t wait until the par- I\njo ticular garment you wish is sold. o\n41\nMr. and Mrs. Thomas Scott spent\nthe week-end in Seaford, Del.\nr Mr. Ralph Ross made a business\ntrip to Philadelphia this week.\nt Mr. Oscar Taylor has accepted a po\nstion with W. S. Schoolfield Co.\nt Mr. Frank B. Matthews, of Balti\nmore, spent Sunday in Pocomoke.\nf Little Miss Esther Eutsler, of Win\nchester, Va., is on a vist to her aunt,\nMrs. A. D. Merrill.\n1 Miss Clara Coston left this week\nfor Annapolis, Md., where she has ac\ncepted a position.\nMessrs. John and Willard Tull, of\nHartford, Conn., were visitors in Po\nccmoke this week.\nMr. and Mrs. Vaughn W. Wilkerson\nspent the last week with the former's\nparents at Mardela, Md.\n1 The Junior Bridge Club was enter\ntained by Mrs. Russell Matthews on\ni Thursday evening of this week.\nMiss Maude D. Stark will spend\nthe coming week in Philadelphia, New\nYork, and Pittsburgh. She will re\nturn January 31 with a line of charm\ning and fascinating millinery.\nMr. Frank U. Barnes, of Williams\nton, N. C., was a visitor to Pocomoke\nfor the last week. Part Of his time\nwas spent in Laurel, Del., on business.\nHe and Mrs Barnes left for their\nhome on Wednesday last.\nMr. E. B. Freeman, now of Norfolk,\nVa., but for many years a resident of\nPocomoke City, was a guest at the\nRotary dinner last Monday evening,\nwhere he met many of his old friends\nwho gave him a cordial welcome.\nOn Tuesday night, Jan, 22, there\nwill be an illustrated lecture on the\nBoy Scout Movement at Salem M. L.\nChurch at 8 o'clock. This lecture will\nbe given by Scout Executive. All\nScouts, Troop N. 1, Pocomoke, their\nparents and friends, are requested to\nbe present.\nCongressman J. Charles Linthicum\nwill be glad to send a copy of the\nlatest Agricultural Year Book (1922\nediton) to anyone interested in read\ning this very valuable work. As he\nrepresents a City district, he has few\ncalls from his own constituents for\nthe Agricultural Year book. Adress\nhim House of Representatives, Wash\nington, D. C.\nit Mr. E. W. Polk left this week fox\nhis annual trip to Florida.\ns Miss Marie Davis arrived home on\nSunday from a visit to Exmore, Va.\nMiss Belle Hudson has arived home\nfrom Hollins College, Roanoke, Va.\nMr. and Mrs. Beverly Crowflon\nspent the week-end in Parksley, Va.\nMiss Annie' Matthews, of Balti\nmore, is visiting her mother, Mjfs.\nJennie Matthews of Fourth street.\nc Mr. and Mrs. Charles D. Potts\nspent last week-end in Baltimore, as\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. J. E. Shea.\nMr. Alma T. Jones is suffering from\na severe attack of rheumatism at the\nhome of his daughter near Stockton.\n1 Mrs. Calloway and daughter, Mrs.\n1 Virginia Trader and Mrs. Alice Daw\nson spent the week-end in Cambridge.\nMr. and Mrs. William Pruitt, Mrs.\n1 Bertha Watson and Misses Irene\nLeonard, Bernice Jefferies and Eliza-\nI beth Cluff, of Chincoteague, Va., at\ntended the installation of officers of\nCrescent Chapter O. E. S., which\ntook place here Monday evening.\n\u201cQuality beyond ques\ntion\u201d is what the makers\ntold us when we bought\nthese tan calf oxfords to\nsell for $5.95.\nOtherwise, we would not\nhave them.\nJust the right silk and\nwool hose, too, to wear with\nthese shoes.\nBAGG(S\nDEPARTMENT STORE\nPOCOMOKE\n*r\nAre You\nReady?\nii 3:\nReading the signs,, they plainly indicate that the 3 3\nj business depression is permanently behind us. 3 3\n3 3 3 Business in general assumes a decidedly more opti- 3\n/J mistic outlook, and the business man with vision is al- 3\n3 ready carefully laying his plans for the business revival j\ni 3 that is upon us.\ns 33\nI One of the first and most important actions should 3 3\nbe your association with the BANK that is in a position 3 3\n!j; to best serve your requirements from a financial and ad- 3 3\nvisory standpoint. 3 3\n33 33\n.J 3 This bank most cordially invites an interview with 3 3\n3 3 any one considering the establishment of new or addi- J 3\nJ 3 tional banking connections.\n1 Hie Citizens National Bank\nOF POCOMOKE CITY\nl BANK HABIT\n33 SAVING HABIT\n33 PROSPERITY\n33 OLD AGE COMFORTS\nX A A. A. A.AX. c\n\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022eeeeeee#\nTned and Approved Plans jj.\n33 For 78 years this Company has confined its busi- j\n3 3 ness to tried and approved plans. Its appeal is 3 3\n3 to those who want pure life insurance with the j 3\n3 most liberal features and at the lowest possible 3 3\n3; COSt.\nThe Mutual Benefit\nLife Insurance Co.\n33 H. M. WALTERS, District Mgr. 33\n\n:i '\u201cJJAMUAET 7 i!\nr lip i\ni mft ii ii\ni|\ni: 7 i:\nfW'A\n\u2022.\u2022ahr lrirs\u2019l solh O\nThe first month of the year\nis a fine time to make your\no first visit